    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            The quadratic formula <m>x = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</m>, is derived from the standard form equation <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m> where <m>a \neq 0</m>, by completing the square.
        </p>
        <p>
            It works for monic (<m>a=1</m>) and non-monic (<m>a \neq 1</m>) equations.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>How to derive quadratic formula:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Step 1:</alert> Start with the standard form of a quadratic equation
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Step 2:</alert> Divide the entire equation by <m>a</m> to make the coefficient of <m>x^2</m> equal to 1
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>x^2 + \frac{b}{a}x + \frac{c}{a} = 0</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Step 3:</alert> Move the constant term to the right side of the equation
        </p>
        <p>
            Subtract <m>\frac{c}{a}</m> from both sides:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>x^2 + \frac{b}{a}x = -\frac{c}{a}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Step 4:</alert> Complete the Square
        </p>
        <p>
            To complete the square, take half of the coefficient of <m>x</m>, which is <m>\frac{b}{a}</m>, divide it by 2 to get <m>\frac{b}{2a}</m>, and then square it to get <m>(\frac{b}{2a})^2</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Add <m>(\frac{b}{2a})^2</m> to both sides of the equation
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>x^2 + \frac{b}{a}x + (\frac{b}{2a})^2 = -\frac{c}{a} + (\frac{b}{2a})^2</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Step 5:</alert> Factor the Left Side as a Perfect Square and Simplify the Right Side
        </p>
        <p>
            The left side is now <m>(x + \frac{b}{2a})^2</m>. For the right side, find a common denominator (which is <m>4a^2</m>)
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>(x + \frac{b}{2a})^2 =\amp (\frac{b^2}{4a^2})-\frac{4ac}{4a^2} </mrow>
                <mrow> (x + \frac{b}{2a})^2 =\amp \frac{b^2-4ac}{4a^2} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Step 6:</alert> Take the square root of both sides and solve for <m>x</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>x + \frac{b}{2a} = \pm \sqrt{\frac{b^2-4ac}{4a^2}}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Simplify the square root on the right side:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>x + \frac{b}{2a} = \pm \sqrt{\frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a^2}}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Step 7:</alert> Solve for <m>x</m>:
        </p>
        <p>
            Subtract <m>\frac{b}{2a}</m> from both sides:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>x = -\frac{b}{2a} \pm \frac{\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Step 8:</alert> Combine the terms on the right side over a common denominator:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>x = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}</m>
        </p>
    </insight> 

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Derive the quadratic formula for the equation <m>x^2 + px + q = 0</m> by completing the square.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Step 1: Start with the standard form of a quadratic equation
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x^2 + px + q = 0</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 2: Move the constant term to the right side of the equation
            </p>
            <p>
                Subtract <m>q</m> from both sides:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x^2 + px = -q</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 3: Complete the Square
            </p>
            <p>
                To complete the square, take half of the coefficient of <m>x</m>, which is <m>p</m>, divide it by 2 to get <m>\frac{p}{2}</m>, and then square it to get <m>(\frac{p}{2})^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Add <m>(\frac{p}{2})^2</m> to both sides of the equation
            </p>
            <p>
                <md><m>x^2 + px + (\frac{p}{2})^2 = -q + (\frac{p}{2})^2</m></md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 4: Factor the Left Side as a Perfect Square and Simplify the Right Side
            </p>
            <p>
                The left side is now <m>(x + \frac{p}{2})^2</m>. For the right side, find a common denominator (which is <m>4</m>)
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>(x + \frac{p}{2})^2 =\amp (\frac{p^2}{4})-q </mrow>
                    <mrow> (x + \frac{p}{2})^2 =\amp \frac{p^2 - 4q}{4} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 5: Take the square root of both sides and solve for <m>x</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md><m>x + \frac{p}{2} = \pm \sqrt{\frac{p^2 - 4q}{4}}</m></md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Simplify the square root on the right side:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md><m>x + \frac{p}{2} = \pm \frac{\sqrt{p^2 - 4q}}{2}</m></md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 6: Solve for <m>x</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                Subtract <m>\frac{p}{2}</m> from both sides:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md><m>x = -\frac{p}{2} \pm \frac{\sqrt{p^2 - 4q}}{2}</m></md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 7: Combine the terms on the right side over a common denominator:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md><m>x = \frac{-p \pm \sqrt{p^2 - 4q}}{2}</m></md>
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Derive the quadratic formula for this equation by completing the square: <m>2x^2 + 3x - 5 = 0</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Step 1: Start with the standard form of a quadratic equation
                <md><m>2x^2 + 3x - 5 = 0</m></md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 2: Divide the entire equation by <m>2</m> to make the coefficient of <m>x^2</m> equal to 1
                <md><m>x^2 + \frac{3}{2}x - \frac{5}{2} = 0</m></md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 3: Move the constant term to the right side of the equation
                <md><m>x^2 + \frac{3}{2}x = \frac{5}{2}</m></md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 4: Complete the Square
                To complete the square, take half of the coefficient of <m>x</m>, which is <m>\frac{3}{2}</m>, divide it by 2 to get <m>\frac{3}{4}</m>, and then square it to get <m>(\frac{3}{4})^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Add <m>(\frac{3}{4})^2</m> to both sides of the equation
                <md><m>x^2 + \frac{3}{2}x + (\frac{3}{4})^2 = \frac{5}{2} + (\frac{3}{4})^2</m></md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 5: Factor the Left Side as a Perfect Square and Simplify the Right Side
                The left side is now <m>(x + \frac{3}{4})^2</m>. For the right side, find a common denominator (which is <m>16</m>)
                <md>
                    <mrow>(x + \frac{3}{4})^2 =\amp \frac{5}{2} + \frac{9}{16} </mrow>
                    <mrow> (x + \frac{3}{4})^2 =\amp \frac{40}{16} + \frac{9}{16} </mrow>
                    <mrow> (x + \frac{3}{4})^2 =\amp \frac{49}{16} </mrow>
                </md>
             </p>
             <p>
                Step 6: Take the square root of both sides and solve for <m>x</m>
                <md><m>x + \frac{3}{4} = \pm \sqrt{\frac{49}{16}}</m></md>
             </p>
             <p>
                Simplify the square root on the right side:
                <md><m>x + \frac{3}{4} = \pm \frac{7}{4}</m></md>
             </p>
             <p>
                Step 7: Solve for <m>x</m>:
                Subtract <m>\frac{3}{4}</m> from both sides:
                <md><m>x = -\frac{3}{4} \pm \frac{7}{4}</m></md>
             </p>
             <p>
                Step 8: Combine the terms on the right side over a common denominator:
                <md><m>x = \frac{-3 \pm 7}{4}</m></md>
             </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
               Using the method of completing the square, derive the quadratic formula for the equation <m>x^2 + \frac{5}{2}x - 3 = 0</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Step 1: Start with the standard form of a quadratic equation
                <md><m>x^2 + \frac{5}{2}x - 3 = 0</m></md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 2: Move the constant term to the right side of the equation
                <md><m>x^2 + \frac{5}{2}x = 3</m></md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 3: Complete the Square
                To complete the square, take half of the coefficient of <m>x</m>, which is <m>\frac{5}{2}</m>, divide it by 2 to get <m>\frac{5}{4}</m>, and then square it to get <m>(\frac{5}{4})^2</m>.
            </p>
                <p>
                Add <m>(\frac{5}{4})^2</m> to both sides of the equation
                <md><m>x^2 + \frac{5}{2}x + \frac{25}{16} = 3 + \frac{25}{16}</m></md>
             </p>
                <p>
                    Step 4: Factor the Left Side as a Perfect Square and Simplify the Right Side
                    The left side is now <m>(x + \frac{5}{4})^2</m>. For the right side, find a common denominator (which is <m>16</m>)
                    <md>
                        <mrow>(x + \frac{5}{4})^2 =\amp 3 + \frac{25}{16} </mrow>
                        <mrow> (x + \frac{5}{4})^2 =\amp \frac{48}{16} + \frac{25}{16} </mrow>
                        <mrow> (x + \frac{5}{4})^2 =\amp \frac{73}{16} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Step 5: Take the square root of both sides and solve for <m>x</m>
                    <md><m>x + \frac{5}{4} = \pm \sqrt{\frac{73}{16}}</m></md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Simplify the square root on the right side:
                    <md><m>x + \frac{5}{4} = \pm \frac{\sqrt{73}}{4}</m></md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Step 6: Solve for <m>x</m>:
                    Subtract <m>\frac{5}{4}</m> from both sides:
                    <md><m>x = -\frac{5}{4} \pm \frac{\sqrt{73}}{4}</m></md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Step 7: Combine the terms on the right side over a common denominator:
                    <md><m>x = \frac{-5 \pm \sqrt{73}}{4}</m></md>
                </p>
        </solution>
    </example> 
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                When simplifying <m>\frac{b^2}{4a^2} - \frac{c}{a}</m>, what do you multiply <m>\frac{c}{a}</m> by to get the common denominator <m>4a^2</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To get the common denominator of <m>4a^2</m>, you multiply <m>\frac{c}{a}</m> by <m>\frac{4a^2}{4a^2}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                This is why the formula contains <m>4ac</m> in the numerator.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

